[[File:Kumanosanshooomiwasha01s1920.jpg|thumb|220px|Torii gate]] [[File:Kumanosanshooomiwasha04s2040.jpg|thumb|220px|Ruins of Hamanomiya Ōji Shrine and Meoto Kusunoki]] [[File:Kumano Kodo Furiwake-ishi.jpg|thumb|150px|Furiwake Stone]]
'''Kumano Sansho Ōmiwasha''' (熊野三所大神社), also known simply as '''Ōmiwasha''' (大神社), is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|Nachikatsuura|ja|那智勝浦町|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nachikatsuura|qq=}}, Wakayama Prefecture, Japan. The shrine enshrines the three deities: Fusumi no Ōkami, Ietsumi no Mikoto no Ōkami, and Hayatama no Ōkami, from which its name derives. The three main deity statues are designated Important Cultural Properties of Japan (1982)<ref>Ministry of Education, Notification No. 98 of 1982.</ref>.
It is built on the site of the former '''Hamanomiya Ōji Shrine''' (浜の宮王子), one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}} shrines along the {{ill|Kumano Kodo|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodo|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}} pilgrimage route. The shrine is also referred to as '''Hamanomiya Ōmiwasha'''. Adjacent to the shrine is {{ill|Fudarakusanji|ja|補陀洛山寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fudarakusanji|qq=}}, reflecting remnants of syncretic Shinto-Buddhist practices. The grounds are part of the UNESCO World Heritage-listed "Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range" (2000)<ref name="Nachi">{{Cite web|ja|url=http://www.town.nachikatsuura.wakayama.jp/div/kyoiku/pdf/bunkazai.pdf|title=Designated Cultural Properties of Nachikatsuura|format=PDF|publisher=Nachikatsuura Town|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>.
== History == Originally a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|-->{{ill|Kumano Nachi Taisha|ja|熊野那智大社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/-->{{ill|qq=}}, it is first mentioned as "Hamanomiya Ōji" in the ''{{ill|Chūyūki|ja|中右記|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūyūki|qq=}}'' in 1109<ref name="Kadokawa">Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Editorial Committee [1985: 233]</ref>. Three Heian-period deity statues (representing Ōyamatsumi, Amaterasu, and Hikohohodemi) suggest it was once dedicated to the {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Gongen|qq=}}. The shrine has undergone several changes in enshrined deities over time.
In the Meiji period, it was separated from Fudarakusanji during the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu bunri|qq=}} reforms, becoming a village shrine in 1873 and later renamed Kumano Sansho Ōmiwasha.
== Cultural Significance == The shrine and its surroundings appear in works such as ''{{ill|The Tale of the Heike|ja|平家物語|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Tale of the Heike|qq=}}'', depicting {{ill|Taira no Koremori|ja|平維盛|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taira no Koremori|qq=}}’s sea departure. The site is also significant for the {{ill|Fudaraku Tokai|ja|補陀洛渡海|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fudaraku Tokai|qq=}} voyages depicted in Nachi pilgrimage mandalas<ref>For details on Nachi pilgrimage mandalas, see Nara National Museum's special exhibition catalog, 2008.</ref>.
The '''Furiwake Stone''' (振分石) on the grounds is believed to mark the division between the Nakahechi and Ōhechi routes of the Kumano Kodo<ref>Kinan Cultural Property Research Group & Kumano Historical Research Society [2008: 83, 95]</ref>.
=== Subshrines === * Tanishiki Totobe no Mikoto (Local deity) * Mikogami (Deity of food) * Wakamiya site (Former Hamanomiya Ōji site)
== Cultural Properties == * '''Wooden Statues of Two Male and One Female Deities''' - Identified as Amaterasu (female), Hikohohodemi (male), and Ōyamatsumi (male). All are seated, carved from kaya wood in the ichiboku-zukuri (single-block carving) style, about 60 cm tall, dating to the late Heian period (11th century). Designated Important Cultural Property (1982)<ref>''Newly Designated Cultural Properties'', Monthly Cultural Property Journal No. 225, Daiichi Hōki, 1982.</ref>. * '''Ruins of Hamanomiya Ōji Shrine''' - Part of the "Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range" (2000)<ref name="Nachi"/>. * '''Stone Lantern''' - Town-designated tangible cultural property (1985)<ref name="Nachi"/>.
== Access == * '''By Train:''' 3-minute walk from {{ill|Nachi Station|ja|那智駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nachi Station|qq=}} on the JR {{ill|Kisei Main Line|ja|紀勢本線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kisei Main Line|qq=}}.
== Nearby Attractions == * {{ill|Nanki-Katsuura Onsen|ja|南紀勝浦温泉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanki-Katsuura Onsen|qq=}}
